      "name": "BL - Brand Review",
      "settings": {
        "section_id": "brand-2",
        "bg_color": "#faf9f7",
        "number": "#2",
        "badge_text": "",
        "brand_name": "Prime Prometics",
        "rating": "4.1",
        "price_text": "$44.00",
        "review_text": "<p>Prime Prometics has built a loyal following among women over 50, and I can see why. The brand clearly understands its audience — the marketing, packaging, and formula are all designed with mature skin in mind. That kind of focus is refreshing in a market that treats 40+ women as an afterthought.</p><p>The color-changing technology works well. Not perfectly — it leaned slightly warm on my cool-toned skin, which meant it wasn't an exact match — but it got close enough that most people wouldn't notice. The texture on application is lovely: creamy, smooth, and easy to blend.</p><p>My main issue is the weight. By mid-afternoon, I could feel it sitting on my skin in a way that became uncomfortable. It also started to emphasize some texture around my cheeks that wasn't visible in the morning. For women with drier skin who don't mind a richer formula, this probably won't bother you. For oily or combination skin, it could be an issue.</p><p>At $44.00, it's a premium price, but the quality of the formula and the brand's genuine commitment to mature skin makes it feel justified — even if it's not the best performer on this list overall.</p>",
        "verdict": "A genuinely good foundation from a brand that takes mature skin seriously. The heavier formula won't suit everyone, but if you run dry and want something with real substance, Prime Prometics delivers.",
        "image_asset": "lp-comparison-foundation-brand-2.jpg",
        "image_position": "left"
      }
    },
