      "name": "BL - Brand Review",
      "settings": {
        "section_id": "brand-5",
        "bg_color": "#faf9f7",
        "number": "#5",
        "badge_text": "",
        "brand_name": "Luxe",
        "rating": "4.0",
        "price_text": "$54.90",
        "review_text": "<p>At $54.90, Luxe is by far the most expensive foundation on this list. The packaging is beautiful — heavy glass bottle, magnetic cap, the whole luxury experience. Opening it feels like an event. But I'm reviewing the formula, not the packaging, and that's where things get complicated.</p><p>The color-changing effect is… subtle. So subtle that I'm not entirely convinced it's doing much at all. On my skin, it barely shifted from its initial beige tone, functioning more like a traditional medium-coverage foundation than the tone-adapting technology it advertises. If the color-change is what you're paying for, this undersells that promise.</p><p>Coverage is actually quite good — the best of the five for concealing age spots and discoloration. The initial application is smooth and the finish looks polished. Where it loses points for mature skin is texture and comfort. The formula is noticeably thicker than the others, and it sits on top of the skin rather than blending in. By hour six, my skin felt tight and dry, and the heavier texture started to look aging rather than perfecting.</p><p>If you want pure coverage and don't care about the color-changing aspect, Luxe is a competent (if overpriced) foundation. But at nearly $55 for a product that barely delivers on its main selling point, it's hard to feel like you're getting value here.</p>",
        "verdict": "Beautiful packaging, solid coverage, but the color-changing technology barely shows up. At this price, you're paying luxury money for a decent traditional foundation that doesn't deliver on its key promise.",
        "image_asset": "lp-comparison-foundation-brand-5.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
    },
